    management: ["Epinephrine IM 0.3-0.5 mg (1:1,000) into lateral thigh as FIRST-LINE; repeat every 5-15 minutes if refractory; transition to IV epinephrine infusion (1-10 mcg/min) for refractory anaphylaxis","IV crystalloid bolus 1-2 L normal saline for persistent hypotension; consider vasopressin 2-10 units IV for catecholamine-resistant shock","Glucagon 1-5 mg IV over 5 minutes for patients on beta-blockers (bypasses beta-receptor blockade via cAMP-independent pathway)","H1 antihistamine (diphenhydramine 50 mg IV) plus H2 antihistamine (famotidine 20 mg IV) as adjuncts; NOT substitutes for epinephrine","Methylprednisolone 125 mg IV or dexamethasone 10 mg IV to reduce biphasic reaction risk (evidence limited but standard practice)","Observation period: minimum 6-8 hours for moderate reactions; 12-24 hours for severe or biphasic-risk patients","Discharge with TWO epinephrine auto-injector prescriptions, anaphylaxis action plan, medical alert identification, and allergist referral within 4-6 weeks"],
